i like peach sorbet & forehead kisses. i like dancing in the shower to the 80s mix that will never grow old & can constantly be heard coming from my bathroom. i like spooning. i like salads that come with lots of vegetables, like cucumbers. i like going to sleep curled up in my down comforter in my in n' out shirt & goldfish boxers. i like the uggs that my grandma gave my dad for christmas but live on my feet. i like my socks (i've bought the same kind for three years). i like hugs that mean something. i like the feeling of waking up after a really good dream. i like dreams in general. i like those really good memories that make you sad but really in the end, made you happy. i like ibooks, the twelve inch ones. i like photographs. i like sitting in a room and seeing someone do something and wishing you could capture it at that moment, if only you had a camera. i like how snowboarder boys dress, i think that it is cute. i like that i don't like the 'typical male' guy that so many girls go after. i like the fact that i'm not a slut. i like that my virginity means something to me. i like god lowercased. i like believing in a higher being such as god. i like that i believe ghosts exist. i like that when i am older, no matter what i'm doing, i'm going to travel. i like inside jokes such as "on a scale of cold to really cold how cold is it? its really fucking cold" & "tapatio". i like music. i like old subarus. i like my cell phone because it is blue. i like my osu sweatshirt complete with stains and all. i like that osu won the civil war game last year. i love my family. i love my pets. i like when carl purrs cause then he isnt mad at me for getting skunk. i like the fact that i will get a job & i will get better. i like that i think diaries are creepy, even though i'm sure they help. i like when boys can make you laugh. i like the smell of rain. i like the top of awbrey butte. i like the top of pilot butte. i like the smoking spot that kenra showed me. i like how falling snow looks under a street lamp. i like this bowl we have in our house that we only have one of. i like the fork that is from chelsea joyces house from when we took cup of noodle from her house to mine and we left the fork here, i always look for that fork in the drawer. i like how cigarette smoke looks when it comes out of your mouth. i like the smell of ralph perfume. i like the smell of laundromats. i like clinique mascara. i like my eyes and my eyelashes. i like boys with pretty eyes. i like boys with skinny calves. i like sandwiches from newport market, i also like their fountain soda. i like pepsi from a fountain in a cup half full with ice, not from a bottle or a can. i like thanksgiving food, especially yams, i also like pumpkin pie from wherever my grandma gets it, it never fails to be satisfying. i liked it when i didn't have my computer to look at ljs and to distract me, i like that i only use AIM express now 'cause i deleted regular AIM. i like my livejournal user pictures cause i am in them with friends & having a good time. i like that sam shares my livejournal with me because it makes me entertained. i like secret livejournals. i like the summers cause fun things happen such as bridge jumping & picnics where creepy men stare.

that's boon(on the left) and the other on is me(xela). I hope to have my own livejournal soon, but for now I'm going to post some pictures on andrea's livejournal anyone have a code they want to give me? if so my screen name is unDonepassion

Stephen just woke up. He rolled out of bed, his hair messy and rough, sticky from the leftover product that embodies it. He had fallen asleep in his clothes, a loosely fit white t-shirt and name brand jeans. A contemplative smile is spread across his face; he looks down at the floor, remembering the previous night's occurances. His forehead is slightly wrinkled, not from age or concern, but from laughter and experience. He puts one hand in his pocket, relaxing his arm. In his other, a burning cigarette, used to calm his morning and ease his nerves. He is leaning against the doorway, the weight of his body resting against his arm. Dark shadows outline the furniture in the room behind him, the light barely profiles the manicured wood and reflects off of the blonde streaks that illuminate his golden brown hair. His t-shirt hangs down across his faded eye-lit belt. His belt is expensive--much like his jeans, it is made to look worn and barely holds up their loose fit. Beside him, the cigarette smoke swirls towards the ceiling, floating up, up, and up, then disappearing into the shadows. He stays standing there for a moment, enveloped in his thoughts, studying the day ahead of him and the nights that are to come. In this moment, he is relaxed.

<center>The time has come for colds and overcoats. We're quiet on the ride, we're all just waiting to get home. Another week away, my greatest fear. I need the smell of summer, I need its noises in my ears. If looks could really kill, then my profession would staring. Please know we do this cause we care and not for the thrill. Collect calls to home to tell them that I realize that everyone who lives will someday die and die alone. And we won't let you in. Though we're down and out. We won't let you in. I wrote more postcards than hooks. I read more maps than books. Feel like every chance to leave is another chance I should have took. Every minute is a mile. I've never felt so hallow. I'm an old abandoned church with broken pews and empty aisles. My secrets for a buck. Watch me as I cut myself wide open on this stage. Yes, I am paid to spill my guts. I won't see home till spring. Oh, I would kill for the Atlantic, but I am paid to make girls panic while I sing. And we won't let you in. Though we're down and out.
We won't let you in. And we won't let you in. We don't want what isn't ours. We won't let you in. You win. And the coastline is quiet. While we're quietly losing control. Yes, we're silent but sure we inventened the cure that will wash out my memories of her. "The harpoon is loaded. The cage is lowered. The water is red." Like you. </center>
